<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1912-11-11T23:59:59-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1912-11-11T00:00:00-05:00" n="1820" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d1820">
                        <note rend="inline" type="source">File No. 367.11/28.</note>
                        <head>
                            <hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">American Ambassador to Great
                                    Britain</gloss> to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                                    State</gloss></hi>.</head>
                        <opener>
                            <seg rendition="#center">[Telegram.—Paraphrase.]</seg>
                        </opener>
                        <opener>
                            <dateline rendition="#right">
                                <placeName>
                                    <hi rend="smallcaps">American Embassy</hi>, <lb/>
                                    <hi rend="italic">London</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1912-11-11">
                                    <hi rend="italic">November 11, 1912</hi></date>.</dateline>
                        </opener>
                        <p>The British Ambassador at Constantinople reports to the Foreign Office
                            that arrangements have been made to accommodate bona fide, American
                            citizens at Constantinople in case of need on board IT. M. S. <hi rend="italic">Weymouth;</hi> protection at other ports is now being
                            arranged for, and would be extended, as Sir Edward Grey understands, in
                            conjunction with other Powers.</p>
                        <closer>
                            <signed>
                                <hi rend="smallcaps">Reid.</hi>
                            </signed>
                        </closer>
                    </div>
                    </body></text></TEI>